{"title_page": "Sophie Gengembre Anderson", "text_new": "{{short description|French-born British artist}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name             = Sophie Gengembre Anderson\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Sophie Gengembre\n| birth_date       = 1823\n| birth_place      = Paris, France\n| death_date       = {{Death date|df=y|1903|3|10}} \n| death_place      = [[Falmouth, Cornwall]], England<ref>Charlotte Yeldham. [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/57068 Biography of Sophie Anderson] (Oxford Dictionary of National Biography - accessed 26 June 2007)</ref><ref>[http://www.drawpaintsculpt.com/artist-biographies/anderson-sophie-gengembre/ Anderson biography] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20111006062819/http://www.drawpaintsculpt.com/artist-biographies/anderson-sophie-gengembre/ |date=2011-10-06 }} (London Atelier of Representational Art at Clapham).</ref>\n| resting_place    = Falmouth Cemetery at Swanvale, Falmouth, England\n| resting_place_coordinates = {{coord|50|8|46.08|N|5|4|38.73|W|type:landmark|display=inline}}\n| nationality      = French-born Britain\n| spouse           = [[Walter Anderson (English artist)|Walter Anderson]]\n| field            = Painting\n| training         = [[Charles de Steuben]]\n| movement         = [[Neoclassism]], Italian [[genre art|genre paintings]]\n| works            = ''No Walk Today,'' ''The children's storybook,'' ''Elaine'' and [[List of works by Sophie Gengembre Anderson|others]]\n}}\n\n'''Sophie Gengembre Anderson''' (1823 &ndash; 10 March 1903) was a French-born British artist who specialised in [[genre works|genre]] painting of children and women, typically in rural settings. She began her career as a lithographer and painter of portraits, collaborating with [[Walter Anderson (English artist)|Walter Anderson]] on portraits of American Episcopal bishops. Her work, ''Elaine'', was the first public collection purchase of a woman artist. Her painting ''No Walk Today'' was purchased for more than \u00a31 million.\n\n==Early life==\n\nSophie was born in [[Paris]], the daughter of Charles Antoine Colomb Gengembre, a French architect and artist,<ref name=\"BritPort\">{{cite book|authors=Brian Stewart & Mervyn Cutten|publisher=Antique Collectors' Club|year=1997|title=The Dictionary of Portrait Painters in Britain up to 1920|ISBN=1 85149 173 2}}</ref> and his English wife, Marianne Farey (1779-1883), a daughter of [[John Farey Sr]] (1766-1826) and his wife Sophia Hubert. They married at St Pancras Church, London, on 12 April 1818 <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Woolrich|first=A.P.|date=1997|title=John Farey, Jr, Engineer and Polymath|url=|journal=History of Technology|volume=vol 19|pages=116|via=}}</ref> Her father was born in 1790 and began working as an architect at age 19. He worked primarily in municipal commissions, like the Mint of the City of Cassel, which he designed and built when he was 19. He was injured during the Revolution of 1830 on the same day that his son Philip was born. The family then went to London, where Gengembre worked as an architect for [[Charles Fourier]]. He returned to France and continued his work as an architect, designing communal schools around France. \n\nThe family moved to America and adopted the surname Hubert, because of difficulties in people pronouncing their french surname.\n\nAfter moving to Cincinnati, Ohio, he settled in Manchester, Pennsylvania, and by 1863 had designed ''pro bono'' the Allegheny City Hall. He stopped speaking English in protest after he was offered a share of the graft of over-inflated construction costs.<ref name=\"Union Dale\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uniondalecemetery.org/notables-detail.php?notableID=+9 |title=Colomb Gengembre|website= [[Union Dale Cemetery]]|accessdate= 6 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nThey lived in Paris during the early years of Sophie's life, where her father was acquainted with artists, intellectuals, and actors, like [[Fran\u00e7ois Joseph Talma]]. Circumstances required that the family leave Paris and live in a \"remote area in France\" from 1829 to 1843.<ref name=\"Benezit1\">{{cite book|authors=|publisher=Editions Grund, Paris|year=2006|title=Benezit Dictionary of Artists Volume 1 A-Bedeschini|ISBN=2 7000 3070 2}}</ref> At seventeen she developed an interest in art when a travelling portrait painter visited her town.<ref name=\"Clayton p. 7\">[[Ellen Creathorne Clayton]]. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=vIZAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA7 English Female Artists]''. Tinsley Brothers, 8 Catherine St., Strand; 1876. pp. 7\u20138.</ref>\n\nShe had two brothers, Philip and Henry P. Gengembre.<ref name=\"haverstock\" /> Her brother Philip changed his name to [[Philip Gengembre Hubert|Philip Hubert]], using his grandmother's maiden name, and was a successful architect in New York City.<ref name=\"Union Dale\" /> She was largely self-taught in art, but briefly studied portrait painting with [[Charles de Steuben]] in about 1843,<ref name=\"haverstock\" /><ref name=\"BritPort\"/> when she lived with family friends in Paris. Soon after she began her studies, he left for Russia and did not return within the one year allotted for her studies. She did develop relationships with other women artists at the school where she gained a little more instruction.<ref name=\"Clayton p. 7\" />\n\n==United States==\n[[File:Sophie Anderson The song of the lark.jpg|thumbnail|left|''The song of the [[lark]]'']]\nThe family left France for the United States to escape the [[Revolutions of 1848 in France|1848 revolution]].<ref name=\"Cornwall Artists\">[http://cornwallartists.org/cornwall-artists/sophie-gengembre-anderson ''Sophie Gengembre Anderson''] Cornwall Artists. Retrieved 6 March 2014.</ref><ref name=\"Benezit1\"/> The family first settled in [[Cincinnati, Ohio]], where she met her future husband, the British genre artist [[Walter Anderson (English artist)|Walter Anderson]]. Her brother Henry P. Gengembre (b. 1825) was also an artist, active in Cincinnati in the early 1850s.<ref name=\"haverstock\" />\n\nHer portrait, figure and Brittany landscape paintings were exhibited in October 1849 at the Western Art Union Gallery. Also exhibited was a three panel set of Victorian London scenes entitled ''The Ladder of Love'', which was described as \"the lady, in her flowery 'May of Life,' awaits in her father's garden a stolen interview with her lover; in the second, she is seen eagerly caught in his impatient arms, ere he has yet left the ladder upon which he surmounted the garden wall; in the third, having received and given reveals of unfaltering love, she walks alone again \u2013 beautiful in the enrobing light of a summer moon, happy in the assurance that the warmth and devotedness of her affection is reciprocated.\"<ref name=\"haverstock\" />\n\nIn 1851 four or more of her illustrations were included in the ''Historical Collections of the Great West'' by Henry Howe.<ref name=\"BritPort\"/> She collaborated with Walter Anderson, her future husband, on portraits of Protestant Episcopal bishops and created other portraits in her business.<ref name=\"haverstock\" />\n\nShe then lived in [[Manchester, Pennsylvania]], with her parents, where she is believed to have married Walter Anderson.<ref name=\"haverstock\" /><ref name=\"BritPort\"/> She worked there for the [[chromolithography|chromolithographers]] [[Louis Prang|Louis Prang & Company]].<ref>D.J. Posner. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=6yBYZcFdIPkC&pg=PA2 Cerebrations of a Flower Child]''. Xlibris Corporation; 19 January 2012. {{ISBN|978-1-4771-6629-1}}. p. 2.{{Self-published inline|certain=yes|date=January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Europe==\n[[File:SophieAndersonTakethefairfaceofWoman.jpg|thumb|A portrait of a fairy (1869). The title of the painting is ''Take the Fair Face of Woman, and Gently Suspending, With Butterflies, Flowers, and Jewels Attending, Thus Your Fairy is Made of Most Beautiful Things'' \u2013 purportedly from a poem by [[Charles Ede]].]]\n\nIn 1854 the Andersons moved to London,<ref name=\"Benezit1\"/> where Sophie exhibited a still life of fruit, vegetables, game and fish entitled ''An American Market Basket'' at the [[Society of British Artists]] by 1855. It was considered an \"admirable composition\" made with \"surprising truth\".<ref>Ellen Creathorne Clayton. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=vIZAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA9 English Female Artists]''. Tinsley Brothers, 8 Catherine St., Strand; 1876. p. 9.</ref> Her genre pieces were also exhibited at the [[Royal Academy]].<ref name=\"CWood\">{{cite book|author=Christopher Wood|publisher=Antique Collectors' Club|year=1978|title=The Dictionary of Victorian Painters|ISBN=0 902028 72 3|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofvict00wood}}</ref> They returned to Pennsylvania in 1858 for a long visit with her family, during which time she exhibited at the Pittsburgh Artist's Association in 1859 and 1860. The latter year she and her husband had work shown at the [[National Academy of Design]]. She then settled in London again around 1863.<ref name=\"haverstock\">Mary Sayre Haverstock; Jeannette Mahoney Vance; Brian L. Meggitt. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=ZdICm_W8xKwC&pg=PA329 Artists in Ohio, 1787\u20131900: A Biographical Dictionary]''. Kent State University Press; 2000. {{ISBN|978-0-87338-616-6}}. p. 329.</ref>\n\n[[File:Sophie Anderson - Elaine - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|''Elaine'' (1870)]]\nAnderson's work was widely exhibited at venues including the Royal Academy, the [[Royal Society of British Artists]] (RBA), and the [[British Institution]].<ref name=Denny>Denney, Colleen . ''At the temple of art: the Grosvenor Gallery, 1877&ndash;1890'' (Fairleigh Dickinson University Press, 2000) p. 130.</ref> Her work, ''Elaine'', was the first public collection purchase of a woman artist.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} The Marquis de Murrieta contributed the painting ''A Fairy Messenger'' to a mixed charity exhibition in 1871.<ref>The painting was in the 'Exhibition for the Benefit of the Distressed Peasantry of France', London in 1871 (no.55) and priced 15 guineas.</ref>\n\nHer oil painting ''Foundling Girls at Prayer in the Chapel'' (mid-c19th \u2013 late-c19th) is displayed at the [[Foundling Museum]]; correlating well with  Anderson's typical genre painting of children and women and the Museum's focus. The painting depicts the varying ages of the foundling girls, what they wore, and references the religious aspects of their life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://foundlingmuseum.org.uk/about/what-is-a-foundling/|title=What Is A Foundling: Foundling Museum|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nTo manage her health issue,<ref name=\"Cornwall Artists\" /> the couple moved to the [[Capri|Isle of Capri]] in 1871, where they lived, painted,<ref name=\"haverstock p. 18\">Mary Sayre Haverstock; Jeannette Mahoney Vance; Brian L. Meggitt. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=ZdICm_W8xKwC&pg=PA18 Artists in Ohio, 1787\u20131900: A Biographical Dictionary]''. Kent State University Press; 2000. {{ISBN|978-0-87338-616-6}}. pp. 18\u201319.</ref><ref name=\"CWood\"/> and entertained society in a house with a large garden called Villa Castello. Capri was an artist colony at that time, its residents included [[Frederic Leighton]], [[Walter McLaren]], [[John Singer Sargent]], [[\u00c9douard Sain|Edouard Alexandre Sain]], and [[Jean Benner]].<ref name=\"FAG\" /><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=mfUPq7S1dZ8C&pg=PA1872 Capri: Island of Pleasure]''. Faber and Faber; 29 November 2012. {{ISBN|978-0-571-29783-2}}. p. 1872.</ref> She exhibited at the [[Grosvenor Gallery]] between 1878 and 1887.  Anderson made Italian genre and [[Neoclassicism|Neoclassical]] paintings, including paintings of peasant women and children. At a time when it was difficult for women to have a successful artistic career, these paintings, generally made by men, allowed for her to have a successful career.<ref>Colleen Denney. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=RvTZrnmy5RoC&pg=PA130 At the Temple of Art: The Grosvenor Gallery, 1877-1890]''. Fairleigh Dickinson Univ Press; 2000. {{ISBN|978-0-8386-3850-7}}. p. 130.</ref>\n\n==Later years and death==\nThe couple moved to England in 1894 and lived and painted in Wood Lane Cottage in [[Falmouth, England|Falmouth]], Cornwall.<ref name=\"Benezit1\"/><ref name=\"CWood\"/> She continued to exhibit her work in London.<ref name=\"Cornwall Artists\" /><ref name=\"haverstock p. 18\" /> On 11 January 1903 her husband Walter died and two months later, on 10 March 1903, she died at home in Falmouth.<ref name=\"haverstock\" /><ref name=\"Cornwall Artists\" /> She was buried at Swanvale cemetery in Falmouth<ref name=\"Cornwall Artists\" /> in the same grave as her husband.<ref name=\"FAG\">[http://www.falmouthartgallery.com/Collection/Artist/Anderson,_Sophie_%281823-1903%29 ''Sophie Anderson.''] Falmouth Art Gallery. Retrieved 6 March 2014.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nA world record price for her work of more than \u00a31 million was achieved by ''No Walk Today'' at [[Sotheby's]], London, in November 2008.<ref name=\"Cornwall Artists\" /><ref>{{cite web|last=Bailey |first=Charlotte |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/3455671/Sophie-Andersons-No-Walk-Today-up-for-sale.html |title=No walk today |publisher=Telegraph.co.uk |date=4 November 2008 |accessdate=2 July 2013}}</ref> It made her \"Cornwall's first million-pound female artist.\"<ref>[https://archive.today/20140307074152/http://www.thisiscornwall.co.uk/Gallery-buys-new-Anderson-work/story-11428882-detail/story.html%23axzz2vGAnaDz2 Gallery buys new Anderson work\"] This is Cornwall. ''The Cornishman''. 11 April 2011. Retrieved 7 March 2014.</ref>\n\nAnderson's work is in the collection of numerous museums and galleries, mainly in the United Kingdom, including New Walk Museum & Art Gallery;<ref name=\"SA BBC\">[https://artuk.org/search/search/search/keyword:sophie-anderson ''Sophie Anderson paintings''.] Your Paintings. BBC. Retrieved March 7, 2014.</ref> [[Leicestershire Museum and Art Gallery]];<ref name=\"Wright p. 67\">Christopher Wright; Catherine May Gordon; Mary Peskett Smith. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=9XNe0mLSJQAC&pg=PA67 British and Irish Paintings in Public Collections: An Index of British and Irish Oil Paintings by Artists Born Before 1870 in Public and Institutional Collections in the United Kingdom and Ireland]''. Yale University Press; 2006. {{ISBN|0-300-11730-2}}. p. 67.</ref> [[Russell-Cotes Art Gallery & Museum]], Bournemouth;<ref name=\"Wright p. 67\" /> [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew]];<ref name=\"Wright p. 67\" /> [[Walker Art Gallery]], Liverpool;<ref name=\"Wright p. 67\" /> [[Birmingham City Art Gallery]];<ref name=\"SA BBC\" /> [[Walsall Museum|Museum and Art Gallery, Walsall]], Staffordshire;<ref name=\"SA BBC\" /> and the [[Wolverhampton Art Gallery]], Staffordshire.<ref name=\"SA BBC\" />\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:SophieAnderson TheTurtleDoveSmall.jpg|''The Turtle Dove''\nFile:Anderson, Sophie Gengembre - No Walk Today.jpg|''No Walk Today''\nFile:Sophie Gengembre Anderson - The Song.jpg|''Birdsong''\nFile:Sophie Gengembre Anderson - Capri Girl with Flowers.jpg|''Capri Girl with Flowers''\nFile:Sophie Gengembre Anderson - Pet canary.jpg|''Pet Canary''\nFile:Sophie Gengembre Anderson Wait for me.jpg|''Wait for Me''\nFile:Sophie Gengembre Anderson - Windfalls.jpg|''Windfalls'' \n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of works by Sophie Gengembre Anderson]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Gaze, Delia (Ed.). ''[[Dictionary of women artists]], Volume 1'' (Routledge, 1997) pp.&nbsp;186\u2013187.\n*Vigu\u00e9, Jordi. ''Great women masters of art'' (Watson-Guptill Pubs., 2003) p.&nbsp;197 ff.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|Sophie Gengembre Anderson}}\n*[http://www.thegreatcat.org/the-cat-in-art-and-photos-2/cats-in-19th-century-art/Sophie-gengembre-anderson-1823-1903-british-french/ Sophie's Cat Paintings]\n*[http://www.artcyclopedia.com/artists/anderson_sophie.html Anderson online] (ArtCyclopedia)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100512131900/http://www.artmagick.com/pictures/artist.aspx?artist=sophie-anderson Paintings by Anderson] (ArtMagick)\n*[http://www.leninimports.com/sophie_anderson.html Sophie Gengembre Anderson's Biography and Gallery] \n*[https://www.the-athenaeum.org/art/list.php?m=a&s=tu&aid=1887 Sophie Gengembre Anderson's artworks] \n*[http://www.thefamousartists.com/sophie-anderson Sophie Gengembre Anderson's life as an artist]\n*[https://www.artfund.org/news/2011/10/10/anderson-painting-returns-to-falmouth-art-gallery Sophie Anderson's ''Roses'' presented to the Falmouth Art Gallery] \n*[http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/walker/collections/paintings/19c/item-235379.aspx Sophie Anderson's ''Elaine'' on display at the Walker Art Gallery]\n\n{{New Woman (late 19th century)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, Sophie Gengembre}}\n[[Category:1823 births]]\n[[Category:1903 deaths]]\n[[Category:English portrait painters]]\n[[Category:Pre-Raphaelite painters]]\n[[Category:Artists from Paris]]\n[[Category:English women painters]]\n[[Category:19th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women artists]]\n[[Category:19th-century British women artists]]\n[[Category:French people of English descent]]\n[[Category:French emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:French emigrants to the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French-born British artist}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name             = Sophie Gengembre Anderson\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Sophie Gengembre\n| birth_date       = 1823\n| birth_place      = Paris, France\n| death_date       = {{Death date|df=y|1903|3|10}} \n| death_place      = [[Falmouth, Cornwall]], England<ref>Charlotte Yeldham. [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/57068 Biography of Sophie Anderson] (Oxford Dictionary of National Biography - accessed 26 June 2007)</ref><ref>[http://www.drawpaintsculpt.com/artist-biographies/anderson-sophie-gengembre/ Anderson biography] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20111006062819/http://www.drawpaintsculpt.com/artist-biographies/anderson-sophie-gengembre/ |date=2011-10-06 }} (London Atelier of Representational Art at Clapham).</ref>\n| resting_place    = Falmouth Cemetery at Swanvale, Falmouth, England\n| resting_place_coordinates = {{coord|50|8|46.08|N|5|4|38.73|W|type:landmark|display=inline}}\n| nationality      = French-born Britain\n| spouse           = [[Walter Anderson (English artist)|Walter Anderson]]\n| field            = Painting\n| training         = [[Charles de Steuben]]\n| movement         = [[Neoclassism]], Italian [[genre art|genre paintings]]\n| works            = ''No Walk Today,'' ''The children's storybook,'' ''Elaine'' and [[List of works by Sophie Gengembre Anderson|others]]\n}}\n\n'''Sophie Gengembre Anderson''' (1823 &ndash; 10 March 1903) was a French-born British artist who specialised in [[genre works|genre]] painting of children and women, typically in rural settings. She began her career as a lithographer and painter of portraits, collaborating with [[Walter Anderson (English artist)|Walter Anderson]] on portraits of American Episcopal bishops. Her work, ''Elaine'', was the first public collection purchase of a woman artist. Her painting ''No Walk Today'' was purchased for more than \u00a31 million.\n\n==Early life==\n\nSophie was born in [[Paris]], the daughter of Charles Antoine Colomb Gengembre, a French architect and artist,<ref name=\"BritPort\">{{cite book|authors=Brian Stewart & Mervyn Cutten|publisher=Antique Collectors' Club|year=1997|title=The Dictionary of Portrait Painters in Britain up to 1920|ISBN=1 85149 173 2}}</ref> and his English wife, Marianne Farey (1779-1883), a daughter of [[John Farey Sr]] (1766-1826) and his wife Sophia Hubert. They married at St Pancras Church, London, on 12 April 1818 <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Woolrich|first=A.P.|date=1997|title=John Farey, Jr, Engineer and Polymath|url=|journal=History of Technology|volume=vol 19|pages=116|via=}}</ref> Her father was born in 1790 and began working as an architect at age 19. He worked primarily in municipal commissions, like the Mint of the City of Cassel, which he designed and built when he was 19. He was injured during the Revolution of 1830 on the same day that his son Philip was born. The family then went to London, where Gengembre worked as an architect for [[Charles Fourier]]. He returned to France and continued his work as an architect, designing communal schools around France. \n\nThe family moved to America and adopted the surname Hubert, because of difficulties in people pronouncing their french surname.\n\nAfter moving to Cincinnati, Ohio, he settled in Manchester, Pennsylvania, and by 1863 had designed ''pro bono'' the Allegheny City Hall. He stopped speaking English in protest after he was offered a share of the graft of over-inflated construction costs.<ref name=\"Union Dale\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uniondalecemetery.org/notables-detail.php?notableID=+9 |title=Colomb Gengembre|website= [[Union Dale Cemetery]]|accessdate= 6 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nThey lived in Paris during the early years of Sophie's life, where her father was acquainted with artists, intellectuals, and actors, like [[Fran\u00e7ois Joseph Talma]]. Circumstances required that the family leave Paris and live in a \"remote area in France\" from 1829 to 1843.<ref name=\"Benezit1\">{{cite book|authors=|publisher=Editions Grund, Paris|year=2006|title=Benezit Dictionary of Artists Volume 1 A-Bedeschini|ISBN=2 7000 3070 2}}</ref> At seventeen she developed an interest in art when a travelling portrait painter visited her town.<ref name=\"Clayton p. 7\">[[Ellen Creathorne Clayton]]. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=vIZAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA7 English Female Artists]''. Tinsley Brothers, 8 Catherine St., Strand; 1876. pp. 7\u20138.</ref>\n\nShe had two brothers, Philip and Henry P. Gengembre.<ref name=\"haverstock\" /> Her brother Philip changed his name to [[Philip Gengembre Hubert|Philip Hubert]], using his grandmother's maiden name, and was a successful architect in New York City.<ref name=\"Union Dale\" /> She was largely self-taught in art, but briefly studied portrait painting with [[Charles de Steuben]] in about 1843,<ref name=\"haverstock\" /><ref name=\"BritPort\"/> when she lived with family friends in Paris. Soon after she began her studies, he left for Russia and did not return within the one year allotted for her studies. She did develop relationships with other women artists at the school where she gained a little more instruction.<ref name=\"Clayton p. 7\" />\n\n==United States==\n[[File:Sophie Anderson The song of the lark.jpg|thumbnail|left|''The song of the [[lark]]'']]\nThe family left France for the United States to escape the [[Revolutions of 1848 in France|1848 revolution]].<ref name=\"Cornwall Artists\">[http://cornwallartists.org/cornwall-artists/sophie-gengembre-anderson ''Sophie Gengembre Anderson''] Cornwall Artists. Retrieved 6 March 2014.</ref><ref name=\"Benezit1\"/> The family first settled in [[Cincinnati, Ohio]], where she met her future husband, the British genre artist [[Walter Anderson (English artist)|Walter Anderson]]. Her brother Henry P. Gengembre (b. 1825) was also an artist, active in Cincinnati in the early 1850s.<ref name=\"haverstock\" />\n\nHer portrait, figure and Brittany landscape paintings were exhibited in October 1849 at the Western Art Union Gallery. Also exhibited was a three panel set of Victorian London scenes entitled ''The Ladder of Love'', which was described as \"the lady, in her flowery 'May of Life,' awaits in her father's garden a stolen interview with her lover; in the second, she is seen eagerly caught in his impatient arms, ere he has yet left the ladder upon which he surmounted the garden wall; in the third, having received and given reveals of unfaltering love, she walks alone again \u2013 beautiful in the enrobing light of a summer moon, happy in the assurance that the warmth and devotedness of her affection is reciprocated.\"<ref name=\"haverstock\" />\n\nIn 1851 four or more of her illustrations were included in the ''Historical Collections of the Great West'' by Henry Howe.<ref name=\"BritPort\"/> She collaborated with Walter Anderson, her future husband, on portraits of Protestant Episcopal bishops and created other portraits in her business.<ref name=\"haverstock\" />\n\nShe then lived in [[Manchester, Pennsylvania]], with her parents, where she is believed to have married Walter Anderson.<ref name=\"haverstock\" /><ref name=\"BritPort\"/> She worked there for the [[chromolithography|chromolithographers]] [[Louis Prang|Louis Prang & Company]].<ref>D.J. Posner. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=6yBYZcFdIPkC&pg=PA2 Cerebrations of a Flower Child]''. Xlibris Corporation; 19 January 2012. {{ISBN|978-1-4771-6629-1}}. p. 2.{{Self-published inline|certain=yes|date=January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Europe==\n[[File:SophieAndersonTakethefairfaceofWoman.jpg|thumb|A portrait of a fairy (1869). The title of the painting is ''Take the Fair Face of Woman, and Gently Suspending, With Butterflies, Flowers, and Jewels Attending, Thus Your Fairy is Made of Most Beautiful Things'' \u2013 purportedly from a poem by [[Charles Ede]].]]\n\nIn 1854 the Andersons moved to London,<ref name=\"Benezit1\"/> where Sophie exhibited a still life of fruit, vegetables, game and fish entitled ''An American Market Basket'' at the [[Society of British Artists]] by 1855. It was considered an \"admirable composition\" made with \"surprising truth\".<ref>Ellen Creathorne Clayton. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=vIZAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA9 English Female Artists]''. Tinsley Brothers, 8 Catherine St., Strand; 1876. p. 9.</ref> Her genre pieces were also exhibited at the [[Royal Academy]].<ref name=\"CWood\">{{cite book|author=Christopher Wood|publisher=Antique Collectors' Club|year=1978|title=The Dictionary of Victorian Painters|ISBN=0 902028 72 3|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofvict00wood}}</ref> They returned to Pennsylvania in 1858 for a long visit with her family, during which time she exhibited at the Pittsburgh Artist's Association in 1859 and 1860. The latter year she and her husband had work shown at the [[National Academy of Design]]. She then settled in London again around 1863.<ref name=\"haverstock\">Mary Sayre Haverstock; Jeannette Mahoney Vance; Brian L. Meggitt. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=ZdICm_W8xKwC&pg=PA329 Artists in Ohio, 1787\u20131900: A Biographical Dictionary]''. Kent State University Press; 2000. {{ISBN|978-0-87338-616-6}}. p. 329.</ref>\n\n[[File:Sophie Anderson - Elaine - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|''Elaine'' (1870)]]\nAnderson's work was widely exhibited at venues including the Royal Academy, the [[Royal Society of British Artists]] (RBA), and the [[British Institution]].<ref name=Denny>Denney, Colleen . ''At the temple of art: the Grosvenor Gallery, 1877&ndash;1890'' (Fairleigh Dickinson University Press, 2000) p. 130.</ref> Her work, ''Elaine'', was the first public collection purchase of a woman artist.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} The Marquis de Murrieta contributed the painting ''A Fairy Messenger'' to a mixed charity exhibition in 1871.<ref>The painting was in the 'Exhibition for the Benefit of the Distressed Peasantry of France', London in 1871 (no.55) and priced 15 guineas.</ref>\n\nHer oil painting ''Foundling Girls at Prayer in the Chapel'' (mid-c19th \u2013 late-c19th) is displayed at the [[Foundling Museum]]; correlating well with  Anderson's typical genre painting of children and women and the Museum's focus. The painting depicts the varying ages of the foundling girls, what they wore, and references the religious aspects of their life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://foundlingmuseum.org.uk/about/what-is-a-foundling/|title=What Is A Foundling: Foundling Museum|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nTo manage her health issue,<ref name=\"Cornwall Artists\" /> the couple moved to the [[Capri|Isle of Capri]] in 1871, where they lived, painted,<ref name=\"haverstock p. 18\">Mary Sayre Haverstock; Jeannette Mahoney Vance; Brian L. Meggitt. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=ZdICm_W8xKwC&pg=PA18 Artists in Ohio, 1787\u20131900: A Biographical Dictionary]''. Kent State University Press; 2000. {{ISBN|978-0-87338-616-6}}. pp. 18\u201319.</ref><ref name=\"CWood\"/> and entertained society in a house with a large garden called Villa Castello. Capri was an artist colony at that time, its residents included [[Frederic Leighton]], [[Walter McLaren]], [[John Singer Sargent]], [[\u00c9douard Sain|Edouard Alexandre Sain]], and [[Jean Benner]].<ref name=\"FAG\" /><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=mfUPq7S1dZ8C&pg=PA1872 Capri: Island of Pleasure]''. Faber and Faber; 29 November 2012. {{ISBN|978-0-571-29783-2}}. p. 1872.</ref> She exhibited at the [[Grosvenor Gallery]] between 1878 and 1887.  Anderson made Italian genre and [[Neoclassicism|Neoclassical]] paintings, including paintings of peasant women and children. At a time when it was difficult for women to have a successful artistic career, these paintings, generally made by men, allowed for her to have a successful career.<ref>Colleen Denney. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=RvTZrnmy5RoC&pg=PA130 At the Temple of Art: The Grosvenor Gallery, 1877-1890]''. Fairleigh Dickinson Univ Press; 2000. {{ISBN|978-0-8386-3850-7}}. p. 130.</ref>\n\n==Later years and death==\nThe couple moved to England in 1894 and lived and painted in Wood Lane Cottage in [[Falmouth, England|Falmouth]], Cornwall.<ref name=\"Benezit1\"/><ref name=\"CWood\"/> She continued to exhibit her work in London.<ref name=\"Cornwall Artists\" /><ref name=\"haverstock p. 18\" /> On 11 January 1903 her husband Walter died and two months later, on 10 March 1903, she died at home in Falmouth.<ref name=\"haverstock\" /><ref name=\"Cornwall Artists\" /> She was buried at Swanvale cemetery in Falmouth<ref name=\"Cornwall Artists\" /> in the same grave as her husband.<ref name=\"FAG\">[http://www.falmouthartgallery.com/Collection/Artist/Anderson,_Sophie_%281823-1903%29 ''Sophie Anderson.''] Falmouth Art Gallery. Retrieved 6 March 2014.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nA world record price for her work of more than \u00a31 million was achieved by ''No Walk Today'' at [[Sotheby's]], London, in November 2008.<ref name=\"Cornwall Artists\" /><ref>{{cite web|last=Bailey |first=Charlotte |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/3455671/Sophie-Andersons-No-Walk-Today-up-for-sale.html |title=No walk today |publisher=Telegraph.co.uk |date=4 November 2008 |accessdate=2 July 2013}}</ref> It made her \"Cornwall's first million-pound female artist.\"<ref>[https://archive.today/20140307074152/http://www.thisiscornwall.co.uk/Gallery-buys-new-Anderson-work/story-11428882-detail/story.html%23axzz2vGAnaDz2 Gallery buys new Anderson work\"] This is Cornwall. ''The Cornishman''. 11 April 2011. Retrieved 7 March 2014.</ref>\n\nAnderson's work is in the collection of numerous museums and galleries, mainly in the United Kingdom, including New Walk Museum & Art Gallery;<ref name=\"SA BBC\">[https://artuk.org/search/search/search/keyword:sophie-anderson ''Sophie Anderson paintings''.] Your Paintings. BBC. Retrieved March 7, 2014.</ref> [[Leicestershire Museum and Art Gallery]];<ref name=\"Wright p. 67\">Christopher Wright; Catherine May Gordon; Mary Peskett Smith. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=9XNe0mLSJQAC&pg=PA67 British and Irish Paintings in Public Collections: An Index of British and Irish Oil Paintings by Artists Born Before 1870 in Public and Institutional Collections in the United Kingdom and Ireland]''. Yale University Press; 2006. {{ISBN|0-300-11730-2}}. p. 67.</ref> [[Russell-Cotes Art Gallery & Museum]], Bournemouth;<ref name=\"Wright p. 67\" /> [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew]];<ref name=\"Wright p. 67\" /> [[Walker Art Gallery]], Liverpool;<ref name=\"Wright p. 67\" /> [[Birmingham City Art Gallery]];<ref name=\"SA BBC\" /> [[Walsall Museum|Museum and Art Gallery, Walsall]], Staffordshire;<ref name=\"SA BBC\" /> and the [[Wolverhampton Art Gallery]], Staffordshire.<ref name=\"SA BBC\" />\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:SophieAnderson TheTurtleDoveSmall.jpg|''The Turtle Dove''\nFile:Anderson Sophie Shepherd Piper 1881.jpg|''Shepherd Piper,'' 1881\nFile:Anderson, Sophie Gengembre - No Walk Today.jpg|''No Walk Today''\nFile:Scheherazade.tif|''[[Scheherazade]]''\nFile:Sophie Gengembre Anderson - The Song.jpg|''Birdsong''\nFile:Sophie Gengembre Anderson - Capri Girl with Flowers.jpg|''Capri Girl with Flowers''\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of works by Sophie Gengembre Anderson]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Gaze, Delia (Ed.). ''[[Dictionary of women artists]], Volume 1'' (Routledge, 1997) pp.&nbsp;186\u2013187.\n*Vigu\u00e9, Jordi. ''Great women masters of art'' (Watson-Guptill Pubs., 2003) p.&nbsp;197 ff.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|Sophie Gengembre Anderson}}\n*[http://www.thegreatcat.org/the-cat-in-art-and-photos-2/cats-in-19th-century-art/Sophie-gengembre-anderson-1823-1903-british-french/ Sophie's Cat Paintings]\n*[http://www.artcyclopedia.com/artists/anderson_sophie.html Anderson online] (ArtCyclopedia)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100512131900/http://www.artmagick.com/pictures/artist.aspx?artist=sophie-anderson Paintings by Anderson] (ArtMagick)\n*[http://www.leninimports.com/sophie_anderson.html Sophie Gengembre Anderson's Biography and Gallery] \n*[https://www.the-athenaeum.org/art/list.php?m=a&s=tu&aid=1887 Sophie Gengembre Anderson's artworks] \n*[http://www.thefamousartists.com/sophie-anderson Sophie Gengembre Anderson's life as an artist]\n*